Ques2-
 To select the lines from a file that have exactly two characters. 
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$ grep -x '..' l2.txt
12
45
99

To select the lines from a file that start with the upper case letter. 
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$ grep -E [A-Z] l2.txt
OS Lab
Richa
Shanbhag


To select the lines from a file that end with a period. 
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$ grep -E '\.$' new.txt
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$  cat -A new.txt
Hello.^M$
bye.^M$
good morning 
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$  tr -d '\r' < new.txt > newfile.txt
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$  grep '\.$' newfile.txt
Hello.
bye.

To select the lines in a file that has one or more blank spaces. 
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$ grep ' ' l2.txt
OS Lab

To select the lines in a file and direct them to another file which has digits as 
one of the characters in that line. 
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$ grep '[0-9]' new.txt > newfile2.txt
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$  cat newfile2.txt
12 am

Ques 3
1) Display the number students( only count) belonging to ICT department. 
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$  vi studentInformation.txt
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$ cat studentInformation.txt
Registration No:Name::Department:Branch:Section:Sub1:Sub2:Sub3
1234:XYZ:ICT:CCE:A:80:60:70
1001:Alice:ICT:CCE:A:85:78:90
1002:Bob:ICT:CCE:A:70:65:75
1003:Charlie:ICT:CCE:B:88:80:85
2450:Riya:CSE:CSE:D:98:95:70
1008:Samay:ECE:ECE:C:70:45:100
1007:Grace:ICT:CCE:A:69:74:71
1009:Ivy:ICT:CCE:C:95:92:89
1010:Jack:ICT:CCE:A:87:90:86
1006:Frank:ICT:CCE:C:90:88:84

student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$  grep -c '^.*:.*:ICT:.*' studentInformation.txt
8

2) Replace all occurrences of IT branch with “Information Technology” and save 
the output to ITStudents.txt
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$ sed 's/:IT:/:Information Technology:/g' studentInformation.txt > ITStudents.txt

3) Display the average marks of student with the given registration number 
“1234” (or any specific existing number).
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$ awk -F':' '$1=="1001" {print ($6+$7+$8)/3}' studentInformation.txt

4) Display the title row in uppercase. The remaining lines should be unchanged. 
student@MIT-ICT-LAB8-5:~/230953054/Lab2$ sed -e '1s/.*/\U&/' studentInformation.txt


