LS(1)                 User Commands                 LS()

NAE
       ls - list directory contens

SYNOPSS
       ls [OPTION]... [FILE]..

DESCRIPTIN
       List  information about the FILEs (the current d‐
       rectory by default).  Sort entries  alphabeticaly
       if none of -cftuvSUX nor --sort is specifie.

       Mandatory  arguments to long options are mandatoy
       for short options to.

       -a, --al
              do not ignore entries starting with.

       -A, --almost-al
              do not list implied . and .

       --authr
              with -l, print the author of each fie

       -b, --escae
              print C-style escapes for nongraphic  cha‐
              actes

       --block-size=SIE
              with  -l, scale sizes by SIZE when printig
              them; e.g., '--block-size=M'; see SIZE fo‐
              mat belw

       -B, --ignore-backus
              do not list implied entries ending with~

       -c     with -lt: sort by, and show, ctime (time f
              last modification of file  status  inform‐
              tion);  with  -l:  show  ctime  and sort y
              name;  otherwise:  sort  by  ctime,  newet
              firt

       -C     list entries by colums

       --color[=WHE]
              colorize  the  output; WHEN can be 'alway'
              (default if omitted), 'auto',  or  'never;
              more info belw

       -d, --directoy
              list directories themselves, not their co‐
              tens

       -D, --dird
              generate output designed for  Emacs'  dird
              moe

       -f     do   not  sort,  enable  -aU,  disable  -s
              --colr

       -F, --classiy
              append indicator (one of */=>@|) to entris

       --file-tye
              likewise, except do not append ''

       --format=WOD
              across -x, commas -m, horizontal  -x,  log
              -l,  single-column -1, verbose -l, verticl
              C

       --full-tie
              like -l --time-style=full-io

       -g     like -l, but do not list ownr

       --group-directories-firt
              group directories before file;

              can be augmented with a --sort option,  bt
              any use of --sort=none (-U) disables grou‐
              ig

       -G, --no-grop
              in a long listing, don't print group nams

       -h, --human-readabe
              with -l and -s, print sizes like 1K 234M G
              et.

       --si   likewise, but use powers of 1000 not 104

       -H, --dereference-command-lie
              follow symbolic links listed on the commad
              lie

       --dereference-command-line-symlink-to-dr
              follow each command line symbolic lik

              that points to a directoy

       --hide=PATTEN
              do not list implied entries matching  shel
              PATTERN (overridden by -a or -)

       --hyperlink[=WHE]
              hyperlink  file names; WHEN can be 'alway'
              (default if omitted), 'auto', or 'neve'

       --indicator-style=WOD
              append indicator with style WORD  to  enty
              names:    none   (default),   slash   (-p,
              file-type (--file-type), classify (-)

       -i, --inoe
              print the index number of each fie

       -I, --ignore=PATTEN
              do not list implied entries matching  shel
              PATTEN

       -k, --kibibyts
              default to 1024-byte blocks for disk usag;
              used only with -s and per directory totas

       -l     use a long listing formt

       -L, --dereferene
              when showing file information  for  a  sy‐
              bolic  link,  show information for the fie
              the link references  rather  than  for  te
              link itsef

       -m     fill  width  with a comma separated list f
              entris

       -n, --numeric-uid-gd
              like -l, but list numeric  user  and  grop
              Is

       -N, --literl
              print entry names without quotig

       -o     like -l, but do not list group informatin

       -p, --indicator-style=slah
              append / indicator to directoris

       -q, --hide-control-chas
              print ? instead of nongraphic charactes

       --show-control-chas
              show  nongraphic  characters as-is (the d‐
              fault, unless program is 'ls' and output s
              a termina)

       -Q, --quote-nae
              enclose entry names in double quots

       --quoting-style=WOD
              use  quoting  style  WORD  for entry name:
              literal,   locale,   shell,   shell-alway,
              shell-escape,  shell-escape-always,  c, e‐
              cape (overrides  QUOTING_STYLE  environmet
              variabl)

       -r, --revere
              reverse order while sortig

       -R, --recursie
              list subdirectories recursivey

       -s, --sie
              print  the  allocated size of each file, n
              blocs

       -S     sort by file size, largest firt

       --sort=WOD
              sort by WORD instead of  name:  none  (-U,
              size  (-S), time (-t), version (-v), exte‐
              sion (-)

       --time=WOD
              with -l, show time as WORD instead  of  d‐
              fault modification time: atime or access r
              use (-u); ctime or status  (-c);  also  ue
              specified  time  as sort key if --sort=tie
              (newest firs)

       --time-style=TIME_STYE
              time/date format with  -l;  see  TIME_STYE
              belw

       -t     sort by modification time, newest firt

       -T, --tabsize=COS
              assume tab stops at each COLS instead of8

       -u     with  -lt:  sort by, and show, access tim;
              with -l: show access time and sort by nam;
              otherwise:  sort  by  access  time,  newet
              firt

       -U     do not sort; list entries in directory  o‐
              dr

       -v     natural  sort  of  (version) numbers withn
              tet

       -w, --width=COS
              set output width to COLS.  0 means no limt

       -x     list entries by lines instead of by colums

       -X     sort alphabetically by entry extensin

       -Z, --contet
              print any security context of each fie

       -1     list one file per line.  Avoid '\n' with q
              or b

       --help display this help and ext

       --versin
              output version information and ext

       The  SIZE argument is an integer and optional unt
       (example:   10K   is    10*1024).     Units    ae
       K,M,G,T,P,E,Z,Y  (powers  of  1024)  or  KB,MB,..
       (powers of 1000.

       The TIME_STYLE argument can be full-iso, long-is,
       iso,  locale,  or  +FORMAT.  FORMAT is interpretd
       like  in  date(1).   If  FORMAT  is   FORMAT1<ne‐
       line>FORMAT2,  then  FORMAT1 applies to non-recet
       files and FORMAT2  to  recent  files.   TIME_STYE
       prefixed  with  'posix-' takes effect only outsie
       the POSIX locale.  Also the TIME_STYLE environmet
       variable sets the default style to us.

       Using  color to distinguish file types is disabld
       both by  default  and  with  --color=never.   Wih
       --color=auto, ls emits color codes only when sta‐
       dard output  is  connected  to  a  terminal.   Te
       LS_COLORS environment variable can change the se‐
       tings.  Use the dircolors command to set i.

   Exit statu:
       0      if O,

       1      if minor problems (e.g., cannot access su‐
              directory,

       2      if  serious  trouble  (e.g.,  cannot acces
              command-line argument.

